    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, im seeing some weirdness in our ec2 instances. getting \"Connection reset by peer\" errors in the logs every few hours but it's totally intermittent. here is a snippet of the cloudwatch log:\n\n2023-10-24T14:22:01Z i-0a1234567890abcdef error: connection reset by peer (errno 104)\n2023-10-24T14:25:12Z i-0a1234567890abcdef error: connection reset by peer (errno 104)\n\nany idea if this could be a security group or NACL thing? or should i look at the app layer?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Connection reset by peer\" errors, especially when intermittent, are a classic sign that something is abruptly closing the connection, which can be caused by a few things. You should definitely check your security groups and Network ACLs first, as those are the first line of defense, or if you're dealing with a specific service, the application layer.\n\nLook at the security group rules associated with those EC2 instances and the network interfaces. Are there any rules that might be dropping traffic unexpectedly? If the network layer is clean, then the issue is likely something on the application side, like a runaway process or a misconfigured connection timeout.",
      "source": "target",
