    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i checked the security groups and the NACLs look okay, no weird rules or anything that would cause a sudden drop. it feels super random though. \n\ncould it be some kind of idle timeout issue? like if a connection sits there too long it just gets killed by the AWS infra or a load balancer? if so, how would i verify if it's the ELB or the instance itself doing the reset?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Idle timeouts, especially when they are random, are a common source of these intermittent connection resets. It's a very good hunch, and you should definitely investigate that.\n\nIf you are using an Elastic Load Balancer (ELB), the ELB has its own timeout settings for idle connections. If a connection sits dormant for longer than the ELB's configured idle timeout, the load balancer will terminate it, which the client perceives as a \"connection reset by peer.\"\n\nTo verify this, you need to check the configuration of your ELB. Look specifically at the idle timeout settings for the target group listeners. If the timeout is set too low, or if your application is just slow to respond between requests, the ELB will be the one doing the chopping.",
      "source": "target",
