    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay, so I checked the ELB idle timeout and it's set to 60 seconds, which seems plenty for our use case. but even then, the resets happen at weird times, sometimes even when we have active traffic. \n\nis there any possibility of some kind of low-level packet interference or a transient network issue within the VPC that could manifest like this? i'm starting to feel like it's some kind of ghost in the machine because there's no logical pattern to it.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the ELB timeout is fine and you're seeing resets even with active traffic, then you're moving into the realm of lower-level, more insidious issues. A transient network issue or packet interference is definitely a possibility, though it's often harder to pin down.\n\nYou might need to look at metrics beyond just the application logs. Check VPC Flow Logs for that specific instance and the load balancer. Flow Logs can show you if packets are being dropped between the instance and the load balancer, or if there are unusual connection resets recorded at the network level.\n\nAlso, consider the health of the underlying network path. Sometimes, the physical infrastructure or the virtual networking fabric within the VPC can have momentary hiccups. A slow, slow-moving problem, like a tiny, persistent packet loss somewhere in the middle, can cause these random resets.",
      "source": "target",
